A circuit breaker works by detecting when a circuit is carrying more electricity than it is designed to handle. This typically happens when an electrical device overheats or a wire shorts, causing the circuit to become energized. When the circuit breaker detects this dangerous situation, it automatically shuts off the power to the circuit, stopping the flow of electricity. The circuit breaker also switches off when it detects a short circuit, where electricity is flowing from a live wire to ground or metal casing.

The circuit breaker features a thermal mechanism that detects heat buildup in the circuit. When the heat exceeds a safe threshold, the thermal mechanism trips a spring-loaded switch, opening the circuit and stopping the flow of electricity. The switch can then be reset once the problem is resolved, allowing the circuit to function normally.
